ese\n[...]\nsystems perform their physiological functions, ojas is\n[...]\nmaintained. Therefore, ojas is the potential source of strength,\n[...]\npower, and natural resistance against illness, which is called\nnatural immunity.\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Subdoṣas/ Ojas, Tejas, and Prāṇa — Vibrational Ayurveda\nURL: https://vibrationalayurveda.com/subdoshas\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Subdoṣas/ Ojas, Tejas, and Prāṇa — Vibrational Ayurveda\n\nMenu\n\n## The Subtle Aspects of Vāta, Pitta, and Kapha\n\nPresented below are charts that provide the 'raw' information on the five subtle aspects (subdoshas) of each dosha. This information can be useful to an Āyurvedic doctor or practitioner when working with a client, as it provides a more localized look at possible causative factors and treatment approaches.\n\n## Ojas, Tejas, and Prāṇa\n\nIn Āyurveda each of the tridoṣa and their comprising elements have a fine and subtle essence in addition to the subdoṣas referenced above. This essence relates to the more subtle of the two elements that primarily compose each doṣa.\n\nFor Kapha doṣa and the water element it is called Ojas.\n\nFor Pitta doṣa and the fire element it is called Tejas.\n\nFor Vāta doṣa and the ether element it is called Prāna.\n\nSome of the primary functions of Ojas, Tejas, and Prāṇa are as follows:\n\n### Ojas\n\nMaintains immunity of bodily tissues; protective energy.\n\nVitality, luster of eyes, glow of skin, subtle substance of the aura\n\nCompassion, contentment, love, clarity, expansion of consciousness.Keeps joints in place.\n\nKeeps doshas in their sites.\n\nMaintains quality & quantity of dhatus, malas & doshas.\n\nNourishes sensory perception.\n\n### Tejas\n\nWhat gives us strength, nutrition, tone of muscles, healthy glow and luster.\n\nThe energy of digestion and transformation of everthing we take in and experience.\n\nCellular intelligence and metabolic activity.\n\nGoverns body temperature.\n\nColor perception.\n\nColor of complexion, eyes & skin.\n\nTactile perception (touch, pressure, pain, temperature).\n\nCellular division and multiplication, cellular permeability of membranes.\n\nUpward movement: going beyond fear and confusion.\n\nStimulates udāna vayu which raises intelligence and levels of consciousness.\n\n### Prāṇa\n\nRespiration, oxygenation, circulation, keeps cells alive.\n\nSustains our life force.\n\nAll sensory and motor functions.\n\nAll mental activity, flow of communication.\n\nThe intake of food, water and air.\n\nThe bridge between body, mind & consciousness.\n\nHolds all particles together.\n\nGoverns the biological functions of ojas and tejas.\n\nPO Box 230488 Anchorage, AK. 99523\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Five Koshas: Yoga's Map of the Layered Self | Digital Dharma\nURL: https://digitaldharma.io/if/yoga-philosophy-koshas-five-sheaths/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: William Le, PA-C\nHighlights:\nThe Taittiriya Upanishad, composed perhaps 2,500 years ago, describes the human being not as a single entity but as five nested sheaths — the pancha koshas — each interpenetrating and each representing a different level of experience. This is not metaphor. It is a phenomenological map that predates but precisely parallels contemporary models in functional medicine, polyvagal theory, and contemplative neuroscience.\n[...]\nThe five koshas are: Annamaya (the food body — physical), Pranamaya (the energy body — vital breath), Manomaya (the mental body — mind and emotion), Vijnanamaya (the wisdom body — discernment and insight), and Anandamaya (the bliss body — the deepest layer of being). Each kosha is described as a sheath (maya = made of, kosha = sheath) surrounding the Atman — the true Self, which is none of the sheaths but the awareness that witnesses all of them.\n[...]\nnamaya kosha — literally “the sheath made of\n[...]\n” — is the densest layer: the\n[...]\nas shaped by what we\n[...]\n, digest, and\n[...]\nThis is the\n[...]\nPranamaya kosha is the layer of vital energy — prana — that animates the physical body. Without prana, Annamaya is a corpse. Pranamaya is the interface between matter and consciousness, between structure and function.\n[...]\nThis kosha encompasses the respiratory system, the autonomic nervous system, and the subtle energy channels (nadis) that yogic anatomy describes. The five pranas (Prana, Apana, Samana, Udana, Vyana) map to distinct physiological functions:\n[...]\n- Prana vayu (inward/upward): respiration, cardiac function, sensory intake\n- Apana vayu (downward/outward): elimination, menstruation, childbirth, immune expulsion\n- Samana vayu (equalizing): digestion, assimilation, metabolic balance\n- Udana vayu (upward): speech, expression, thyroid function, growth\n- Vyana vayu (pervasive): circulation, nerve impulse conduction, peripheral distribution\n[...]\nPranayama\n[...]\nPranamaya kos\n[...]\nIn traditional Chinese medicine, Pranamaya kosha corresponds to qi — the vital energy that flows through meridians and is regulated through acupuncture, qigong, and tai chi. The parallel is not superficial: both systems describe an intermediate layer of energetic organization between the physical body and the mind, and both have developed sophisticated technologies for its regulation.\n[...]\nKosha |\n[...]\nAnnamaya\n[...]\nNutrition, supplements, asana, manual therapy, medication |\n| Pranamaya\n[...]\nPranayama, acupuncture, HRV biofeedback, vagal toning |\n| Manomaya\n[...]\nPsychotherapy, CBT, EMDR, journaling,\n[...]\nprocessing |\n| Vijnanamaya\n[...]\nMeditation, contemplative practice, spiritual direction, IFS |\n[...]\nnidra, deep meditation, ceremony, nature immersion |\n\n---\n\nTitle: Prana, Tejas, Ojas, Nadis and the Chakras of the Subtle Body — Elements Healing & Wellbeing\nURL: https://www.elementshealingandwellbeing.com/blog/prana-tejas-ojas-nadis-and-the-chakras-of-the-subtle-body-042-2\nPublished: 2018-08-23T16:15:00.000Z\nAuthor: Written By  Colette Kent\nHighlights:\nPrana, Tejas, Ojas, Nadis and the Chakras of the Subtle Body — Elements Healing & Wellbeing\n\n# Episode 042: Prana, Tejas, Ojas, Nadis and the Chakras of the Subtle Body\n\nAug 23\n\nColette delves deeper into the subtle body. According to Ayurveda, the subtle body represents the energetic field behind the physical body. Along with the mind, the emotions and deep thought, the subtle energies of Prana, Tejas and Ojas work at this level, along with the nadis and the chakras.\n\nColette discusses the following:\n\nPrana – our life force energy\n\nTejas – our radiance and courage\n\nOjas – our immunity and strength\n\nThe Nadis – the subtle energy channels through which prana flows\n\nThe 7 Chakras or energy vortexes of the body according to Ayurveda\n\nColette completes this episode with a Chakra meditation\n\nIf you’re interested in learning more about the upcoming group, online cleanse or a private cleanse, please click on the link below….\n\nAyurvedic Reset Cleanse\n\nClick on the link below to access the Pranayama tutorial (scroll down to podcast Episode #25 Pranayama video tutorial). Check out the Nadi Shodhana or Alternate Nostril Breathing pranayama that Colette recommends…\n\nPranayama (breath work) video tutorial\n\nThank you for listening!\n\nListen to the Elements of Ayurveda Podcast on the Go!\n\nApple- Amazon Music- Spotify- Google Play- Stitcher- Tunein- Deezer- iHeart Radio- YouTube\n\n#### READY TO GET STARTED WITH AYURVEDA?\n\n#### Book a free 15-minute enquiry call with Colette\n\nColette Kent\n\n## Episode 043: Behaviour Changes with Amy Wheeler\n\nPrevious\n\n## Episode 041: Ayurvedic Nutrition with Joyful Belly\n\nNext","_meta":{"searchTime":1972.1}}]}
