xercise, sleep, and lifestyle.\n[...]\nUnlike generic wellness apps that give everyone the same advice, Shaanti uses artificial intelligence to analyze your Ayurvedic constitution—whether you're Vata (air), Pitta (fire), or Kapha (earth)—and creates customized guidance for diet, daily routines, sleep protocols, and seasonal adjustments.\n[...]\nOur comprehensive 25-question AI-powered assessment determines your birth constitution (Prakriti) and current imbalance (Vikriti). Get personalized diet, routine, and lifestyle recommendations in just 5 minutes.\n[...]\nShaanti is a personalized wellness platform rooted in 5,000 years of Ayurvedic wisdom and powered by modern AI technology.\n[...]\nWe help you discover your unique body type, then give you ongoing guidance for every wellness decision you make. From what to eat to how to move to when to rest.\n[...]\nReceive weekly rituals, seasonal protocols, and wellness recommendations tailored to your constitution. No more guessing what will work.\n[...]\nAsk our AI any wellness question and get instant answers based on your unique constitution.\n[...]\nEvery week, receive practices specifically designed for your constitutional type and current state.\n[...]\n## Start with a 7-day free trial on monthly plans\n[...]\n$10/month\n[...]\n- Complete constitutional assessment and body type discovery\n- AI-powered guidance for any product or practice\n- Weekly personalized rituals based on your unique constitution\n- Seasonal rebalancing protocols\n- Quarterly reassessments as you evolve\n- Monthly deep-dive wellness manuals\n- Expert-curated recommendations that actually work for you\n[...]\nTry free for 7 days. Card required. No charge until day 8. Cancel anytime.\n[...]\nPlan 2: Annual\n[...]\n$100/year\n[...]\n2 months free\n[...]\n- Complete constitutional assessment and body type discovery\n- AI-powered guidance for any product or practice\n- Weekly personalized rituals based on your unique constitution\n- Seasonal rebalancing protocols\n- Quarterly reassessments as you evolve\n- Monthly deep-dive wellness manuals\n- Expert-curated recommendations that actually work for you\n[...]\nPay once per year. Best value for committed wellness seekers.\n[...]\nNo credit card required for assessment. Free trial available on monthly plans.\n\n---\n\nTitle: FindMyHealth - Company Profile | All You Need To Know\nURL: https://startuptalky.com/findmyhealth-success-story/\nPublished: 2021-05-17T07:30:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\njourney started with an\n[...]\nto use technology to bring the power of Ayurveda and alternative medicine to more people\n[...]\nThe biggest gap which\n[...]\nav saw to start with was helping people identify what herbs to take, many people were consuming\n[...]\nhoc recommendations from friends and family\n[...]\nFindMyHealth (website), the company's first offering allows users to get a peek into their inner health, based on an Ayurvedic framework of what health is. It starts with a face selfie analysis to identify the body constitution and visual aging/obesity, which is followed up by a conversation with their AI doctor to identify the state of the inner functional health.\n[...]\nThis together is used to generate a detailed health fingerprint of the user and identify recommendations for herbs, foods, and a healthy lifestyle. They also offer a personalized supplement, which compounds all the recommended herbs into a single pill for supporting health and recovery.\n[...]\nThe FindMyHealth business model works on a freemium model, the assessment is free (so is the identification of the right herbs). They intend to monetize the personalized supplement that is custom-built for the user. They will also have personalized diet plans very soon. Right now, the company has two paid offerings on the website - personalized Ayurvedic herb mix for INR 999 and therapeutic (disease reversal diet plans) for INR 6,999.\n[...]\nhas worked for\n[...]\n, people find it unique and it enables high click-through rates and\n[...]\n. While the\n[...]\nbrings users, their\n[...]\nhealth help keep them. According to the company, more than 60% of the users are going through completing\n[...]\n, sometimes spending up to\n[...]\n10 minutes on it, which is a lot in terms of internet time.\n[...]\nis the distinctive benefit of their AI, enabling them to identify the unique health situation of an individual and connect them to appropriate targeted actions drawn from the wisdom of Ayurveda and other natural techniques. An additional strong aspect of the company's technology is that it can be done in a non-invasive manner and remotely on the app.\n[...]\nHaving just launched, the company is nearing\n[...]\n20,000 completed\n[...]\non the platform\n[...]\n- starting from deep assessment\n[...]\ntechnology products that support individuals' journeys back to balance and good health.\n[...]\nteam of technologists, data scientists\n[...]\nselfie analysis and health score identifies\n[...]\nOne can start seeing improvements in one month, however, findmyhealth recommends that you take them for a minimum of three months. If you take a three-month subscription, they will recommend you to retake the online assessment every month.","_meta":{"searchTime":1082.8}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_04imb9of749c_4","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Towards standardization of Prakriti Evaluation: A scoping review of modern assessment tools and their psychometric properties in Ayurvedic medicine - PMC\nURL: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12269270/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThis scoping review aims to identify modern Prakriti assessment tools available in scientific literature and describe their psychometric properties to contribute to the development of more effective and standardized methods for Prakriti evaluation. Employing Arksey and O'Malley's five-stage methodological framework, the review critically assesses Prakriti evaluation tools, such as questionnaires, machine learning algorithms, and devices, to provide insights into the robustness and accuracy of these assessment methods.\n[...]\nThirty-two studies meeting the inclusion criteria were included in the review. Sixteen studies utilized questionnaires for Prakriti assessment, of which three were validated, six had established reliability, and three had both reliability and validity confirmed. Five studies employed algorithm-based methods, with three of these using validated machine learning models. Eleven studies utilized devices to assess Prakriti types, with only one device validated and providing access to data for reproducibility. Questionnaires were the most commonly used tools for Prakriti evaluation, followed by algorithm-based methods and devices.\n[...]\nWe evaluated the psychometric properties of the questionnaire-based Prakriti assessment tools using three reliability measures: internal consistency, test-retest reliability, and inter-rater reliability [[25], [26], [27], [28], [29]]. Additionally,\n[...]\nvalidity measures were used:\n[...]\nvalidity, criterion validity, and\n[...]\nvalidity [26,[30], [31], [32], [33], [34],\n[...]\nFor the assessment of machine learning models, we used reproducibility, cross validation methodology, and standard performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F-measure, specificity, sensitivity [[37], [38], [39], [40], [41]]. The ground truth labelling method was also carefully analysed and assessed.\n[...]\nAmong the questionnaires reviewed, eleven used the self-assessment format, six used the interview-styled format, and two used both. The questionnaires evaluate extreme, dual, and balanced\n[...]\n, validity, and their different\n[...]\nhave been used to evaluate the robustness of\n[...]\nquestionnaires. While the questionnaire contains\n[...]\nin the range of twenty to one hundred\n[...]\n-seven, only\n[...]\nof them explicitly asked the respondents to fill in their\n[...]\n, which persisted over a long period of time to ensure that\n[...]\nand not the current state of doshas,\n[...]\n., vikriti\n[...]\nLikewise, out of\n[...]\ntotal questionnaires reviewed\n[...]\nremaining one is\n[...]\n, it cannot\n[...]\nriti Analysis Tool (\n[...]\nAT) [5\n[...]\n], are comparatively better cited in the available literature. In\n[...]\npart of this subsection, we discuss each Questionnaire in more detail.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Development of a standardized assessment scale for assessing  Prakriti  (psychosomatic constitution)\nURL: https://journals.lww.com/aayu/fulltext/2022/43040/development_of_a_standardized_assessment_scale_for.1.aspx\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe study was conducted on a designed PAS for its validation in terms of face, content, construct, and criterion validity. The reliability testing of the validated PAS has been evaluated through intra-rater and inter-rater reliability testing estimated using the Kappa statistic.\n[...]\nWhile reviewing the existing formats and software being used by various academic and research organizations for*Prakriti*assessment, it was observed that comprehensive characteristic features as described in major Ayurvedic classics for the*Prakriti*assessment are not considered. Moreover, as the characteristic features for*Prakriti*assessment are mostly subjective in nature, there is a possibility of variation in uniform assessment of an individual’s*Prakriti*by different assessors based on their understanding and experience to capture the characteristic feature. Hence, it was felt that a detailed and exhaustive study is necessary to develop a standardized*Prakriti*Assessment Scale (PAS) with standard operative procedures which can capture the*Prakriti*of an individual with rationality, reliability, reproducibility, and maximum objectivity. Undertaking research with a “whole system” approach of Ayurveda by applying the latest technologies such as molecular biology and the recently developed field of ‘omics with an attempt to provide an explanation and interpretation of concepts in terms of globally accepted language, re-establish concepts in current perspective, standardize traditional treatment principles, assessment of therapeutic claims, and validation is pertinent and need of the hour.*Prakriti*assessment through a standardized PAS will help in prescribing diet and lifestyle advocacy for preventive and promotive health. This information can be successfully applied clinically in diagnosis, treatment (for deciding the appropriate drug, dose, duration, diet, and lifestyle), and prognosis of the disease.*Prakriti*can help in the assessment of the individual for physical and mental strength, appetite, likes and dislikes, and adaptability to food and medicines, etc.\n[...]\nThe objective was to develop and validate an assessment scale as per the standardized methodology of questionnaire development for assessing the Ayurvedic*Prakriti*of an individual with rationality, reliability, reproducibility, and maximum objectivity.\n[...]\nThe result of the\n[...]\npredictors for assessment of*Prakriti*were prepared. In the process of\n[...]\nKappa provides the degree of agreement beyond chance\n[...]\nindividual is generated, the data cannot be edited or changed which ensures the authentication of the report. Any particular information required about the*Prakriti*of a person can be presented in various statistical formats easily.\n\n---\n\nTitle: N/A\nURL: https://public-pages-files-2025.frontiersin.org/journals/medicine/articles/10.3389/fmed.2025.1656249/pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nPrakriti or constitutional typology is the foundation of personalized\n[...]\nhealth care in Ayurveda. Traditionally, Ayurvedic clinicians have assessed Prakriti\n[...]\nin a primarily experience-based and often subjective manner. However, in\n[...]\nthe past few decades attempts to develop objective tools have been made\n[...]\nby researchers from multidisciplinary domains. This review aimed to identify\n[...]\nexisting Ayurvedic Prakriti assessment tools and evaluate their scientific rigor.\n[...]\nmet the inclusion criteria. Prakriti assessment tools were quantified and evaluated\n[...]\nusing Scale Development and Validation Framework by Boateng et al., alongside\n[...]\ncustom set of study quality indicators to assess their methodological rigor.\n[...]\nPrakriti assessment\n[...]\nTo address this methodological\n[...]\ngap, we\n[...]\nsearch yielded six\n[...]\nsources, comprising\n[...]\nand five journal articles (\n[...]\n41–44)\n[...]\nfocused on scale\n[...]\n, the “Scale Development and Validation Framework” by Boateng\n[...]\net al. (35), was selected for this study. We\n[...]\nthe original figure\n[...]\nWe evaluated the tools and their adherence to the\n[...]\nmethodological steps in the framework\n[...]\nthe rubric. Each PAT\n[...]\nwas qualitatively evaluated against the\n[...]\nsteps of the Boateng\n[...]\nframework using a scoring rubric (Supplementary Appendix 1);\n[...]\nfulfillment of at least one specific analysis or procedure per step (\n[...]\nFA/C\n[...]\nfor dimensionality)\n[...]\nvariation across studies\n[...]\nWe evaluated all the identified PATs using a holistic scoring rubric \n(Supplementary Appendix 1) based on the identified Framework by \nBoateng et al. (35), and found that out of 64, only 20 PATs have undergone\n[...]\nsome form of validity and reliability testing using standard methods. The\n[...]\nresult of this analysis is given in Figure 5.\n[...]\nWe found that no tool looked at all 9 steps spanning the three\n[...]\nphases listed in the framework. Two tools, the CCRAS-PAS software\n[...]\n(45) and the Ayurveda Child Personality Inventory (ACPI scale) (46)\n[...]\nfulfilled seven out of nine steps defined in the evaluation framework\n[...]\n, the TSSC-SAQ (47) fulfilled 6 of the 9 steps\n[...]\nkappa, and\n[...]\n20\n[...]\ns. In\n[...]\nterms of validity,\n[...]\nvalidity, and\n[...]\nvalidity were most applied, while predictive and\n[...]\ndiscriminant validity were rarely used.\n[...]\nOverall, the review found that of the 64 unique\n[...]\n20\n[...]\ntools, the CCRAS-PAS software and the\n[...]\nscale demonstrated notable methodological rigor\n[...]\nwas validated in\n[...]\nPI scale was specifically developed and tested for\n[...]\nuse in children\n\n---\n\nTitle: Development and validation of a Prototype  Prakriti  Analysis Tool (PPAT)\nURL: https://journals.lww.com/aayu/fulltext/2012/33020/development_and_validation_of_a_prototype_prakriti.10.aspx\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nWe have also seen that the current methods of*Prakriti*diagnosis have not been validated before their use. It is for this reason that inter-rater and intra-rater variability among the results obtained is a frequent observation.[13] Recently, researchers (2011)[14] have approached to develop and validate a self-assessment tool of*Prakriti*examination. This study, however, cross-examined the newly developed tool against one commonly used tool which itself was not validated statistically. Moreover, self-assessment tools are often considered less reliable compared to physician’s examination for propensity of former toward better choices among the offered options.[13] Considering the difficulties observed in conventional*Prakriti*determination, CDAC has developed Ayusoft software where*Prakriti*can be determined with the help of a computer-assisted questionnaire.[15] Though good, this approach still requires validation by making it largely available to Ayurvedic hospitals and research institutes and by cross-checking the inferences generated by this. It is also observed that a*Prakriti*examination made through conventional ways gives us only a proportional idea about the predominance of certain*dosha*upon the others. It, therefore, does not explain about the*Doshagunas*which are actually responsible for a particular*Dosha*expression. It is important to understand that*Doshagunas*are the primarily the classes of attributes which ultimately determine the expressions in a particular*Dosha*group. Every*Dosha*has got its different set of*Gunas*, and the features pertaining to every*Doshaprakriti*are in correspondence to these*Gunas\n[...]\nConsequently, the conventional method of*Prakriti*examination does not offer any help to clinical decision making in conditions where predominance of a*Dosha*is required to be judged further in terms of expressing\n[...]\nis important to understand here\n[...]\nevery*Dosha*is a composite of certain\n[...]\nthe expression of certain variables coming under its ambit\n[...]\nFrom Ayurvedic perspective, therefore\n[...]\nlimitations observed in current methods employed in*Prakriti*determination, we developed a prototype*Prakriti*analysis tool (PPAT) for a rapid, yet dependable diagnosis of*Prakriti*, including the identification of specific*Guna*components of*Dosha*responsible for such a dominance in an individual. For their intricate complexities and philosophical tenets, standardization\n[...]\ndiagnostic tool can be judged for\n[...]\nindependent observers in reference to*Prakriti*determination of the same subjects.[17],[18]\n[...]\nContent validity of any interrogatory tool is concerned with how well the individual items in the tool correspond to the concept of what is being measured\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Brief Prakriti Inventory: Latent structure, reliability, and validity\nURL: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41523163/\nPublished: 2026-01-16T18:00:18.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Brief Prakriti Inventory: Latent structure, reliability, and validity\n\n## Abstract\n\nBackground: Ayurveda, the traditional Indian medicine system, conceptualizes individual personality (Prakriti) through three dimensions, Vata, Pitta, and Kapha, based on physical, physiological, and psychological traits. Existing tools for Prakriti assessment often lack robust psychometric validation and accessibility. We developed and validated the Brief-Prakriti Inventory (BPI), a 21-item self-report instrument for assessing traditional Indian personality concepts.\n\nMethods: An initial 30-item pool was derived from classical Ayurvedic texts and contemporary literature, covering three domains. Following pilot testing and psychometric screening, 21 items were retained. Items used nominal response formats, each mapped to a dosha, with randomized option order via REDCap. Psychometric evaluation employed Multiple Correspondence Analysis (MCA), Latent Class Analysis (LCA), and Item Response Theory (IRT) in a community sample (N = 1857). Validity was assessed via test-retest reliability, convergent validity with traditional AYUsoft assessments, and divergent validity using Western personality traits (Mini-IPIP).\n\nResults: MCA revealed distinct dosha-aligned item clustering, particularly among participants with dominant dosha profiles ( Figure 1). LCA supported a three-class model (dominant-only: entropy R2 = 0.96) ( Figure 2, Supplementary Figure 1). IRT analyses showed strong fit (CFI = 0.967, RMSEA = 0.023) and good reliability (Vata = 0.87, Pitta = 0.75, Kapha = 0.87) ( Figure 3). Psychological items showed highest discrimination; physiological items displayed higher difficulty thresholds. Test-retest reliability was high (ICCs 0.83-0.90). BPI subscales correlated strongly with traditional assessments (r = 0.78-0.84) (Supplementary Figure 2) but minimally with Western personality traits ( Figure 4), supporting construct distinctiveness.\n\nConclusions: The BPI is a brief, reliable, psychometrically validated self-report tool that captures latent dosha typology consistent with Ayurvedic theory. By grouping individuals into Prakriti-based clusters, the BPI will enable biological phenotyping of dosha-linked variability and support personalized, culturally contextualized interventions in integrative and mental health care.\n\nKeywords: Ayurveda; Individual Differences; Personality Assessment; Prakriti; Psychometrics; Traditional Medicine.\n\n## Grants and funding"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"22c4bbb1-1289-478e-91c5-aaf533a8b7ce","uuid":"dda886c7-3745-4ebd-9e68-44de17cab749","timestamp":"2026-06-10T22:37:00.088Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Towards standardization of Prakriti Evaluation: A scoping review of modern assessment tools and their psychometric properties in Ayurvedic medicine - PMC\nURL: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12269270/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThis scoping review aims to identify modern Prakriti assessment tools available in scientific literature and describe their psychometric properties to contribute to the development of more effective and standardized methods for Prakriti evaluation. Employing Arksey and O'Malley's five-stage methodological framework, the review critically assesses Prakriti evaluation tools, such as questionnaires, machine learning algorithms, and devices, to provide insights into the robustness and accuracy of these assessment methods.\n[...]\nThirty-two studies meeting the inclusion criteria were included in the review. Sixteen studies utilized questionnaires for Prakriti assessm